    </p>
    <table xml:id="TABLEBasicIntegration">
      <title>Integration Rules Inherited from Differentiation Rules</title>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row bottom="major" header="yes">

          <cell>#</cell>
          <cell>Differentiation Rule</cell>
          <cell>
            <line>Integration  Rule</line>
            <line> (In all cases <m>C</m> is an arbitrary  constant.)  </line>
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>1</cell>
          <cell><m>\dx(\text{constant})=0</m></cell>
          <cell><line><m>\displaystyle\int0\dx{x}=C</m>, where <m> C
          </m> is a constant.</line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>2</cell>
          <cell><m>\dx(f+g)=\dx{f}+\dx{g}</m></cell>
          <cell>
          <line><m>\displaystyle\int\dx(f+g)=\int\dx{f}+\int\dx{g}</m><m>=f+g+C</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>3</cell>
          <cell>
            <line>If <m>a</m> is a constant, then<m>\dx(ay)=a\dx(y)</m></line>
          </cell>
          <cell>
          <line><m>\displaystyle\int a\dx{y}=\int\dx(ay)=a\int\dx{y}</m><m>=ay+C</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>4</cell>
          <cell><m>\dx(x^{n+1})=(n+1)x^n\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int x^n\dx{x} = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C, n\neq
          -1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>5</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\ln(x))=\frac1x\dx{x}=x^{-1}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int x^{-1}\dx{x} = \ln\abs{x}+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>6</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(e^x)= e^x\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int e^x\dx{x} = e^x+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>7</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sin(x))=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int \cos(x)\dx{x} = \sin(x) +C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>8</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\cos(x))=-\sin(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int \sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x) +C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>9</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\tan(x))=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>10</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}=\sec(x)+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>11</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))=
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>12</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))=
          \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+C</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>13</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))=
          \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+C</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>


    <p>
      The solution strategy we used when we rewrote <xref
      ref="EQUATIONSpinCastDiffeq">equation</xref> is called
      <term>separation of variables</term> and it will enable us to solve
      a great many simple differential equations.
    </p>
    <p>
      To see this consider the differential equation

      <men xml:id="EQUATIONSepVar1">\dfdx{y}{x} =xy</men>.
    </p>
    <problem>
      <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
      <p>
        Before we continue see if you can come up with a solution of <xref
        ref="EQUATIONSepVar1">equation</xref> on your own.<!--  Notice how it is -->
        <!-- similar to, and different from, <xref -->
        <!-- ref="IVPExpGeneral">equation</xref>. Does that help? -->
      </p>
    </problem>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLESepVar">
      <!-- <title>Separation of Variables</title> -->
      <p>
        Separating variables is not new. This is how you were taught to
        solve algebraic equations. For example, suppose we want to solve
        the algebraic equation

        <men xml:id="EQUATIONycubedeqxy">y^3-x^2y - 6y=0</men> for <m>y</m>.
        One obvious solution is <m>y=0</m>. This is a valid solution, but
        it is uninteresting, so we will not consider it.  Assuming that
        <m>y\neq 0</m>, we can divide by <m>y</m> obtaining

        <me>y^2-x^2-6=0</me> 

        At this point  we separate the variables     by
        rearranging the terms algebraically so that  all of the terms
        involving <m>y</m> are on 
        on one side, and all of the terms involving <m>x</m> (or involving
        neither <m>x</m> nor <m>y</m>)  on the
        other
        <me>y^2=x^2+6</me>.
        It is clear that
        the expression on the right is positive so  we can take the
        square root of each side and obtain <m>y=\pm \sqrt{x^2+6}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that it was
        not immediately clear that separating the variables would be
        helpful but once it was done, the next step was clear. 
      </p>
      <p>
        It is similarly  not clear that separating the variables in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONSepVar1">equation</xref> will help, but let<rsq/>s try
        it and see what happens.
        Separating the variables, we see that

        <me>\frac{\dx{y}}{y}=x\dx{x}</me>  which says that the differentials on
        either side of the equation are the same.  Integrating (summing)  both
        sides gives
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONSepVar2">\int{\frac{1}{y}} \dx{y}=\int{x\dx{x}}</men>.

      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <idx><h>Problems</h></idx>

      <introduction>
        <p>
          <idx><h>Problems</h></idx>
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Integrate both sides of <xref ref="EQUATIONSepVar2">equation</xref>
            and then show that <m>y</m> must satisfy


            <me>\ln \abs{y}+C_1=\frac{x^2}{2}+C_2</me> 
            where <m>C_1,\ C_2</m> are arbitrary constants.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that 
            <me>y=\pm \left(e^{C_2-C_1}\right)e^{\frac{x^2}{2}}</me>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          Since <m>C_1,\ C_2</m> are arbitrary constants, it follows that <m>
          e^{C_2-C_1}</m> is also an arbitrary constant. (Why?) For simplicity
          we will set <m>A=e^{C_2-C_1}</m>, so <m>y=\pm Ae^{\frac{x^2}{2}}</m>
          provides the general solution for the original differential equation.
        </p>
      </conclusion>

    </exercise>


    <p>
      It is not always possible to separate variables. For example, try
      separating the variables in <m>y=\sin(xy)</m> or
      <m>\dfdx{y}{x}=\cos(xy)</m>. You won<rsq/>t get far.
    </p>
    <p>
      Even when it is possible it is not always helpful.  For
      example, suppose we had the algebraic equation
      <me>y^3=x+y</me>.
      Separating the variables gives <m>y^3-y=x</m>, but it would take an
      application of the <term>Cubic Formula</term> which is not so
      trivial.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        The 
        <term>Cubic Formula</term> is like the 
        <term>Quadratic Formula</term>, only more fun.
      </p>
    </aside>


    <p>
      There are whole books and college courses, at both the undergraduate
      and graduate levels, on the solution of various kinds of differential
      equations, and it is still an active area of mathematical research.
      Separable differential equations are among the simplest to solve but
      even these can be quite challenging at times.
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMSeparableDiffeqs">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> (if necessary)
          to confirm that the function <m>y</m> shown solves the
          separable differential equation.
          Then find the most general solution.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>

        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{x} = (1+x)(1+y)</m>, <m>y=
            (1+x)e^{\frac{x^2}{2}+x}</m>
          </p>

        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{x} = 9x^2y^2</m>,
            <m>y=\frac{-1}{3x^3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{x}=x^3\inverse{y}</m>, <m>y=\frac{x^2}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dx{y}+2xe^{-y}\dx{x} =0 </m>, <m>y=-2\ln(x)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{x}=x^3\sec(y)</m>,   <m>y=\frac{x^3}{\sqrt{1-\left( {x^4}/{4}\right)^2 }}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>(1+t^2)\dx{y}=(1+y^2)\dx{t} </m>, <m>y=t</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            You might find this helpful:           <m>\tan
            (a+b)=\frac{\tan(a) +\tan(b) }{1-\tan(a) \tan(b){}}</m>
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Find the pattern</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the most general solution.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t} = (1+x)(1+y)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t} = (2+x)(3+y)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t} = (2+4x)(3+5y)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t} = 7(2+4x)(3+5y)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Assume  that <m>\alpha{}</m>, <m>\beta{}</m>,
            <m>\gamma{}</m>, <m>\delta{}</m>, and <m>\kappa{}</m> are
            all constant:
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t} = \kappa (\alpha +\beta x)(\gamma +\delta y)</m>
            </p>
                </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>




    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMFirstOrderLinearDiffeq">
      <title>Find the pattern</title>
      <task>
        <p>
          Solve the differential equation 
          <me>y^{\prime} +2y =0 </me>
          (This is a <term>first order</term> differential equation
          because  the  
          highest order derivative that appears in
          it is the first.)
        </p>
      </task>
      
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the differential equation 
            <me>y^{\prime\prime} +2y^\prime =0 </me>
            (This is a <term>second order</term> differential equation
            because  the  
            highest order derivative that appears in
            it is the second.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Make it <q>easier on your eyes.</q>
          </p>
        </hint>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Make the substitution: <m>z=y^\prime </m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the differential equation 
            <me>3y^{\prime\prime\prime} -5y^{\prime\prime} =0 </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            What is the order of this differential equation?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMHomogeneosDiffeqs">
      <title>A Homogeneous Equation</title>

      <introduction>
        <p>
          Consider the differential equation <men
          xml:id="EQUATIONHomogeneous">y^2\dfdx{y}{t}=2ty+y^2 </men>.
          As stated this is not a separable equation nor is there any
          other obvious way to find <m>y(t)</m>. But with a little
          cleverness we can turn it into a separable equation.
        </p>
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   Use the substitution <m>y=ut</m>, where -->
        <!--   <m>u=u(t)</m> is an unknown differentiable function, to turn -->
        <!--   this into a separable differential equation. -->
        <!-- </p> -->
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that if <m>y=ut</m> then <m>\dfdx{y}{t} =
            u+t\dfdx{u}{t}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            This substitution is the <q>cleverness</q> we referred to
            above. The rest is computation. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the substitution from part (a) to reduce  <xref
            ref="EQUATIONHomogeneous">equation</xref> to 
            <me>t\dfdx{u}{t} = u+u^2</me>
            which is separable.            
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Now separate the variables in the equation in part (b)
            and integrate 
            to obtain 
            <me>\int \frac{1}{u(u+1)}\dx{u} =\ln\abs{t}+C </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show  that 
            <me>\frac{1}{u(u+1)}=\frac1u-\frac{1}{u+1}</me> and use
            that knowledge to compute the integral in part (c).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Finally show that 
            <me>y(t)=\frac{\kappa t^2}{1-\kappa t}</me> where
            <m>\kappa{}</m> is an arbitrary constant.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Unlike parts (a) through (d) there is more than one step
            to complete  part (e). Several more, in fact. Proceed
            carefully and check your work.
          </p>
        </hint>

      </task>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          It should be clear to you that the substitution <m>y=ut</m>
          is what made this solution possible. Without that we had no
          place to begin.           However, once the substitution was made the path ahead was
          clear.
        </p>
        <p>
          But as you<rsq/>ve just seen even when the path
          ahead is clear, computing the solution of a differential
          equation can be a tedious and painstaking process. Proceed
          slowly, check your work frequently, and be careful.
        </p>
        <p>
          <xref ref="EQUATIONHomogeneous">Equation</xref> is an
          example of a <term>homogeneous
          equation</term>. Unfortunately it investigating this idea
          any further would take us too far afield so we
          won<rsq/>t. See if you can make up other differential equations
          where that substitution will also work. Then look at what
          they have in common. You just might be able to work out the
          meaning of <q>homogeneous</q> in this context on your own.
        </p>
      </conclusion>

    </exercise>
    
    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEHardDiffeq">
      <title>The Hanging Chain, again</title>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref> of <xref
        ref="SECTIONhyperb-trig-hang"></xref> we saw that if <m>y(x)</m>
        is the shape that a hanging chain naturally settles into under the
        pull of gravity then <m>y(x)</m> will necessarily be a solution of
        the second order differential equation:
        
        <men  xml:id="EQUATIONHangChainModel">
          \dfdxn{y}{x}{2} =
          \frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}.
        </men>

        which is a model for the Hanging Chain problem. That is, the graph
        of a function which solves <xref
        ref="EQUATIONHangChainModel">equation</xref> will be the shape of
        a hanging chain.
      </p>

      <p>
        It is one thing to confirm a given solution, as you did in
        <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref>, but as you<rsq/>ve
        seen finding the solution in the first place is not always a
        simple task. We can<rsq/>t actually derive the solution of
        this equation yet, but we have developed enough tools to get
        started.
      </p>
      <p>
        First we  let <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m>, so that        
        <men>
          \dfdx{z}{x}=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+z^2}.
        </men>
        Separating the variable next we see that 
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z} =\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}
          </men>.

          <!-- As we saw in <xref ref="DIGRESSIONDifferentialNotation">DIGRESSION: -->
          <!-- Differential Notation</xref> the product of a number and a -->
          <!-- differential is a differential so  -->
          <!-- <xref ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">equation</xref> says that every -->
          <!-- differential of the form <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}</m> is -->
          <!-- equal to a differential of the form <m>\frac{w}{H}\dx{z} -->
          <!-- </m>.  -->
          Integrating  both sides of <xref
          ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">equation</xref>, we see that
          <men  xml:id="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">
            \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{w}{H}\dx{x} =
            \frac{\omega}{H}x+C
            </men>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Unfortunately nothing in our <xref
      ref="TABLEBasicIntegration" text="custom">table of integrals</xref>  quite matches the left hand
      side of <xref ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">equation</xref> so
      we can<rsq/>t take this problem any further right now. 
      We<rsq/>ll return to it after we have developed more integration
      techniques.
    </p>

    <p>
      However we can confirm the solution if it is already known. We did
      this in <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref>.
    </p>

    <problem  xml:id="DRILLHangingChainSolution">
      <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
      <p>
        Confirm (again) that
        <me>y=\frac{H}{2w}\left(e^{\frac{wx}{H}}+e^{-\frac{wx}{H}}\right)</me>
        is the solution of<xref
        ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">equation</xref>.
      </p>
    </problem>


  </section>

